<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-069-782  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 069 782.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 20 1989 v23 n7 p60(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Don't start without IT. (information technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnston, Russell.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The planning methodologies companies use when trying to gain acompetitive advantage through the implementation of informationtechnology is directly related to the success of those informationtechnology projects.andP;  Blending the assessment of informationtechnology options into strategy formulation improves informationintensity quotient of corporate strategy, provides a two-waylearning experience between information systems managers andhigh-level business managers and brings the organizationalstructure to the present.andP;  Information systems managers notprepared to do so should make an immediate effort to acquirewhatever skills and knowledge necessary to contribute to theformulation of corporate strategy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information TechnologyCompaniesStrategic planningManagement of EDPImplementation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>